c esp html a new benchmark test to assess Effective System Performance NERSC s 6 656 processor http hpcf nersc gov computers SP IBM RS 6000 SP has 416 16 CPU POWER3 SMP nodes with a peak performance of 10 teraflop s making it the most powerful computer for unclassified research in the United States The system has 7 8 terabytes of aggregate memory and a Global Parallel File System with 44 terabytes of storage NERSC has named this system seaborg in honor of the late Nobel laureate Dr Glenn Seaborg longtime associate director of Berkeley Lab Additional capabilities are provided by two special purpose servers a computers servers newton php cluster of 4 PC s running Linux for numerical and statistical processing and a computers servers escher php Silicon Graphics Onyx 3400 for scientific visualization from remote locations To stay ahead of the growing needs of our clients and the growing capacity of our computational systems NERSC works constantly to increase the capacity bandwidth and functionality of our storage hpss HPSS mass storage system As of March 2003 HPSS provides 35 terabytes of disk cache and an archival storage capability of 8 8 petabytes NERSC s research in data intensive computing is grounded in our operation of a major production facility the PDSF http pdsf nersc gov Parallel Distributed Systems Facility The PDSF is a 390 processor Linux cluster used by large scale high energy and nuclear physics investigations for detector simulation data analysis and software development The PDSF s 48 disk vaults provide a total 35 TB of data storage Access to NERSC from anywhere in the U S or the world is available through http www es net ESnet which provides network OC 48 bandwidth to NERSC 2 5 gigabits per second Gb s OC 192 bandwidth on major backbone links 10 Gb s and OC 3 155 Mb s and OC 12 622 Mb s links over much of the rest of its coverage area In November 2000 NERSC s computing and storage systems moved from Berkeley Lab s main site to the Oakland Scientific F